These behavioural predictions, however, cannot reveal hidden cognitive mechanisms [10]. To address this, we fit hierarchical Bayesian experience-weighted attraction (EWA) models—originally developed for human strategic behaviour [31]—to infer four latent learning parameters that could jointly underpin material choices:
ϕ, how rapidly males refine material preferences (asocial information updating);
λ, how strongly males exhibit material preferences (asocial information weighting);
ϵ, how elastically males react to deposited social material (social information updating);
σ, how much males consider asocial versus social information (social information weighting).
